(157, 4, 'My grandmother is quite an old lady. She has already crossed sixty. Her years have now bent her back a little but have not affected her activities. She is tall and thin. She is grey haired and her humble and affectionate face is full of wrinkles. Her eye-sight, however, is quite good and she can read without spectacles. <br><br>She is a religious lady. She is the first to leave her bed in the morning. Before we get up, she has already taken her bath with fresh water. Immediately after taking a bath, she goes to the nearby temple. We eagerly wait for her to come back, for she usually brings sweets for us. Even at this age, she is very active and hard-working. She is very affectionate and caring. We, her grandchildren, are attached to her more than to our parents<br><br>She is the most respected lady in our colony. Ladies, young and old, come to her for advice. Sometimes they bring their problems. Sometimes she tells them her own experiences. They listen to her respectfully.<br><br>When we were little kids, she used to be such a source of joy. We used to wait eagerly for night because at night all of us snuggled near her and then she would tell stories like Mahabharat, Ramayan, Panchtantra, etc.<br><br>What is the main idea of paragraph 3?', 'The women in the colony respect each other.', 'The women in the colony respect the writers story.', 'The writers grandmother is respected in her colony.', 'The writers grandmother respects the colony.', 'c', ''),
